The paper discusses a problem in HCI research, specifically the estimation of cognitive model parameters from behavioral data. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of approximate Bayesian computation (ABC) to condition model parameters to data and prior knowledge, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the fitting of models to individual users, which suggests that it may belong to the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the theoretical implications of using ABC for model parameter inference, which suggests that it may also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
